{{Infobox book | name = Fayan | title_orig = {{no italic|法言}} | translator = | image = | caption = | author = [[Yang Xiong (author)|Yang Xiong]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = China | language = [[Classical Chinese]] | series = | genre = [[Philosophy]] | publisher = | release_date = c. AD 9 | english_release_date = | media_type = | pages = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} {{Infobox Chinese |c=《{{linktext|法|言}}》 |l=''Model Sayings'' |p=《Fǎyán》 |w=''Fa Yen'' |mi={{IPAc-cmn|f|a|3|-|yan|2}} |gr=Faa Yan |j=Faat<sup>3</sup> jin<sup>4</sup> |y=Faat Yìhn |tl=Huat Giân |mc={{IPA|Pjop ngjon}} }} The '''''Fayan''''',<!--Chinese in infobox; see WP:MOS-ZH--> also known in [[English language|English]] as the '''''Model Sayings''''' or '''''Exemplary Figures''''', is an [[Classical Chinese|ancient Chinese]] text by the [[Han dynasty]] writer and poet [[Yang Xiong (author)|Yang Xiong]] that was completed around {{sc|ad}}{{nbsp}}9. It comprises a collection of dialogues and aphorisms in which Yang gives responses to a wide variety of questions relating to philosophy, politics, literature, ethics, and scholarship.{{sfnp|Knechtges|2010|p=213}}
==Contents== The text of the ''Fayan'' is divided into 13 chapters. It is presented in the form of dialogues between Yang and an anonymous interlocutor who asks him questions, to which Yang responds with terse, authoritative pronouncements that rely more on wit and puns than on logical exposition.{{sfnp|Knechtges|1993|p=100}} The style is deliberately{{sfnp|Knechtges|2010|p=213}} modeled on the ''[[Analects]]'' of [[Confucius]]{{sfnp|Knechtges|2010|p=100}} and was intended to counter the ideas of the "syncretic" philosophical school, which Yang believed was contrary to the orthodox teachings of [[Confucianism]] and the ancient Chinese sages.{{sfnp|Knechtges|2010|p=213}}
